bug.short_desc: [persistence] Existing RSE Workspaces cannot be used with RSE I20060811-1150

long_desc.thetext:
When RSE is updated in an existing workspace, it tries to read existing connection data from the "RemoteSystemsConnections" project.
But, because file formats have changed, data is not read correctly. Essentially, RSE becomes unusable, because also creating new connections leads to exceptions. What's making things really bad, is that there is no command to clear the connection data and start with a fresh connections project!
Only workaround is to make sure that the RemoteSystemsConnections Project is deleted before updating RSE.
I think we should implement some safeguard against these problems -- at least such that when a new version of the file formats is detected, a dialog should pop up asking the user to delete the old connections.
This dialog could also help in the future, when we might want to migrate old connections. For now - since 1.0 is not yet released - deleting old data is OK, no migration is necessary.

There needs to be a migration mechanism for persistent data if the format needs to change. This can be done using different persistence providers, but the mechanism for specifying them needs to be worked out.
When persistent data is migrated, the old data should be placed in an archived form in case it is needed for diagnostic or recovery purposes.

I don't think we are going to fix this, since RSE 1.0 is not yet released.
In case we change the file formats after release, a migration path will need to be considered.

1) Download the Eclipse SDK Source Build distribution, eclipse-sourceBuild-srcIncluded-3.2.1.zip

5) Set the compiler environment variable used by the .mak file to SunONE (shell-dependent): CC=[path_to_compiler_installation]/bin/cc
6) Link to the GNU make (it wont work with SunONEs make!): which gmake | sed s|\(.*\)|ln s \1 make| | sh

bug.short_desc: Article explaining how to implement basic editor functionalities in GEF

long_desc.thetext:
Simply put an editor is a visualization component in an Eclipse application which is typically used to edit and browse a document or any kind of persistent store. In contrast to views that save changes made to the workbench immediately, an editor follows an open-modify-save-close paradigm. An example of this is the Java editor in the Eclipse workbench.
This article will explain how to implement an Eclipse plug-in using a GEF based editor. This article refrains from explaining everything at once and thus some (crucial) topics like wizards, actions & menus are explained in follow-up articles.

bug.short_desc: Article explaining how to combine a view with a GEF application

long_desc.thetext:
While views are the same as editors in many ways, there certainly are some important differences. The most apparent one is that any action performed in a view should immediately be propagated to the workbench and thus all underlying resources. A view restricts access to information in a way that users are only able to browse information, but never ever (I mean it) change this information. Editing information is done by editors and that is the topic of another article.
This article explains how to implement an Eclipse plug-in using views. These views will use an in-memory model as a basis to visualize figures on the canvas.

long_desc.thetext:
A complex type has defined sequence of elements. The minOccurs and maxOccurs constraints were set to 1. If the element is missing in xml, the EObjectvalidator reports "missing feature.." correctly. But if there are more than 1 elements in xml, the EObjectvalidator does not report any error.
For example, the schema defines.. <complexType name="Employee"> <sequence minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="1"> <element name="address" type="es:Address"/> </sequence> </complexType>

Those plug-ins should not use any of the SWT or JFace specific parts, and the only way to enforce this is to put the SWT and JFace code into a separate plug-in.

bug.short_desc: Refactor out templates into a separate plugin(s)

Here are my reasons in a random order of importance
1) The common case here is you have products that build on PDE. The products use PDE or even modify it (in our case, we modify it). There are cases when products don't want to ship with PDE's normal templates, they would want to ship with their own. So, instead of modifying PDE, you just drop another plug-in to ship.
2) PDE UI is huge
3) This is a good case of plug-in refactoring. My definition of when to make things a plug-in is when they have no strict dependency on the host. PDE UI can live w/o templates.
I somehow managed to convince Wassim this was a good idea, but I forgot what I bribed him with ;)

(In reply to comment #7) I don't want to stand in the way but do want to understand.
> 1) The common case here is you have products that build on PDE. The products > use PDE or even modify it (in our case, we modify it). There are cases when > products don't want to ship with PDE's normal templates, they would want to > ship with their own. So, instead of modifying PDE, you just drop another > plug-in to ship.
Is there a real need to remove the templates from PDE in product scenarios? A product that offers the developer a chance to develop plugins but does not allow them to use the basic templates seems a bit strange. Adding templates sure. I assume that the template set is already extensible no?
> 2) PDE UI is huge
not particularly compelling
> 3) This is a good case of plug-in refactoring. My definition of when to make > things a plug-in is when they have no strict dependency on the host. PDE UI can > live w/o templates.
Yes, but the question is whether or not anyone really wants it to live without the templates. What is the scenario under which someone would not ship the template bundle?
> I somehow managed to convince Wassim this was a good idea, but I forgot what I > bribed him with ;)
yeah but Wassim is easy. Or is it cheap...

> (In reply to comment #7) > Is there a real need to remove the templates from PDE in product scenarios? A > product that offers the developer a chance to develop plugins but does not > allow them to use the basic templates seems a bit strange. Adding templates > sure. I assume that the template set is already extensible no?
Sure, there are products that build on top of PDE that work with special runtimes (for example, the new suite coming out of Lotus that are Eclipse-based). It is useful to reuse the PDE templating system for templates that apply for the specific product in question. There are cases when developers of products would want end-users to only use their templates. Is it easier to drop a bundle from your Eclipse-based product containing all of PDE's templates or to go hand pick out the plugin.xml to remove references to PDE's templates so your's only show up? (Brian, can you chime in here about your experience of building on top of PDE for a product)
Another point is that some of the new work that Kim Horne is doing around product customization could help with this problem. However, I don't think that's the right approach for this particular problem.
Also a point to make is that PDE isn't really considered a platform yet by any means, but in the future, with small steps like these (and exposing the ability for other OSGi Frameworks to use PDE), PDE becomes easier to consume.
This should be a fairly easy refactoring, we're not doing something like refactoring the runtime into several plug-ins ;)

I think comment 9 is spot on. We have seen several examples of people building products on top of Eclipse and wanting to control/modify/replace the list of templates PDE ships.
Also, the Austin chapter of the PDE team has threatened to go on a hunger strike until the templates are refactored into a separate plug-in. Their demands are reasonable, and we really don't want to deal with a coup d'etat at this time.

bug.short_desc: XML Driver not recognizing ISO8601 Timestamp values

long_desc.thetext:
XML driver currently does not recognize ISO8601 format date/time value (such as '2006-08-09T14:23:11'). This needs to be fixed since this is the standard XML date/time format defined in XML Schema (http://www.w3.org/TR/NOTE-datetime).
The XML driver, when parsing a date/time string, should (1) FIRST attempt to parse any of the following formats. Note that if a timezone portion is present, the timestamp value should be converted to UTC by subtracting the TZ offset from the timestamp value.
Complete date: YYYY-MM-DD (eg 1997-07-16) Complete date plus hours and minutes: YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm (eg 1997-07-16T19:20) Complete date plus hours, minutes and seconds: YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss (eg 1997-07-16T19:20:30) Complete date plus hours, minutes, seconds and a decimal fraction of a second YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss.s (eg 1997-07-16T19:20:30.45)
An optional time zone offset may immediately follow a date/time values that contain a time portion. The offset can take one of the following forms Z (UTC time zone; e.g., 1997-07-16T19:30:21Z) +hh:mm (hh:mm ahead of UTC. E.g, 1997-07-16T19:30:21+02:00, two hours ahead of UTC) -hh:mm (hh:mm behind UTC. E.g, 1997-07-16T19:30:21-05:00, US Eastern time, 5 hours behind UTC) If the time zone offset is absent, UTC timezone is assumed.
(2) If the above parsing fails, it should attempt to parse using the user locale setting like it does right now.
Add support for ISO8601 date/time formats in XML driver.

The problem has to do with our current limitation of not being able to immediately recognize that when the included jspf is modified, jsps including the jspf file should update their jsp/java translation model.

Okay, I see what you are saying now. There are 2 big issues: 1) getting the right model to validate based on what type of validation we want to do (source-latest/dirty model vs batch-last saved model)
2) reporting the problems in the open editor (there will be confusion over what is reported from batch validation in the problems view vs source validation in the editor when editor is dirty)
For problem #1, currently, I believe we only generate/allow 1 model per file, so when the file is open in the editor, the model we use is always going to be the latest/possibly dirty model. To get this working, we may need a change to the model manager, and it will probably be a pretty big change.

bug.short_desc: Server connectors must support separate startup and shutdown vm args

long_desc.thetext:
We are working with the platform mbean server which is required of all Java 5+ jvms and we have encountered a usability problem with the WTP server connectors. Mainly when the jvm is started we pass the following 3 options as vm args
-Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.port=<port #> -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.authenticate=false -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.ssl=false
which is correct when starting the server. However when shutting down the server you can't pass these options because the jvm used to shutdown the server will again try and bind to the port used to startup the server which will fail with an address already in use exception. The end result is that we can't shutdown nor restart the server from inside eclipse. We either have to use external scripts to perform a shutdown/restart or we just have to terminate the server instance.

What exactly are you asking here? Components have no control over the VM arguments that you use to launch the JVM with. Shouldn't the server (or at least the start/stop commands) be run in a different JVM?

The problem is easy to reproduce and from that it should be simple to understand the usability problem. Start an Apache Tomcat 5.5.x server instance with the following additional vm args "-Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.port=1099 -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.authenticate=false -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.ssl=false". You do not need to actually deploy anything to it. Once the server has started up, now _try_ and shut it down or restart it via the server connector. You can't. The reason is that the tomcat server config has on the Arguments tab a text field for "Program arguments", which contains "start" and a text field for "VM arguments", which contains "-Dcatalina.base="E:\dev\workspace-eclipse\.metadata\.plugins\org.eclipse.wst.server.core\tmp0" -Dcatalina.home="E:\dev\apache-tomcat-5.5.17" -Djava.endorsed.dirs="E:\dev\apache-tomcat-5.5.17\common\endorsed" -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.port=1099 -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.authenticate=false -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.ssl=false".
Starting and stopping tomcat requires 2 jvms, 1 and 2 respectively. JVM 1 uses the last 3 options to bind to port 1099 and start the tomcat server. All is fine at this point. However, when you try and shutdown/restart tomcat another jvm is used, JVM 2. JVM 2 is also given the same vm args which will lead jvm 2 to try and bind to port 1099 again. This will fail because jvm 1 (the tomcat server) is still bound to it, thus JVM 2 will exit before it ever got the chance to run the Apache code to shutdown/restart JVM 1.
So all in all the launch configs need separate startup and shutdown program arguments and vm arguments.
I hope this is clearer.
This in an implementation detail of the Tomcat adapter, and we could use a different adapter or just strip out the properties... is that what you're looking for?

(In reply to comment #3) > This in an implementation detail of the Tomcat adapter, and we could use a > different adapter or just strip out the properties... is that what you're > looking for? >
I haven't looked at the code but I figure this is a general problem that just manifests itsself easily with the server connectors that execute java processes to start, stop, restart, publish, etc to the server instance. I don't think we can just strip them out though. In this case that would work but what if there are properties defined for a security manager, endorsed directories, etc. We would simply be rearranging deck chairs with out addressing the real issue. The real issue is that for server connectors that execute java process, the user needs to be able to add/remove vm args for each process action (Start, Stop, Restart, Publish). As I said this only affects connectors that execute java processes to do the actual work. Connectors that work across HTTP, RMI or custom protocols would not exhibit this problem since a new jvm with the same vm args would not be created.
What's the movement/resolution on this defect?
*** Bug 157222 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

This bugzilla will be used for the Tomcat server adapter. Although this is a general issue, Tomcat is the only real case where this applies today in WTP.
Larry - Assigning to you since you said you could take a look at your dup bug.

Tim,
It should be no problem to incorporate something for WTP 2.0. I'm curious whether you think we need a limited fix for WTP 1.5.2.
At least "com.sun.management.jmxremote*" properties could be removed, since these properties aren't totally unexpected, which would get us past this specific issue. I would need to verify, but it may be that what is returned by ITomcatVersionHandler.getRuntimeVMArguments() is sufficient for "stop" and we could just skip the "merge" of the other existing arguments.

Isn't the more general solution to simply add 2 textfields to the tomcat server adapter? One field contains startup vm args and the other contains shutdown vm args. The reason this seems like a WTP issue is because in the normal case no thought to test it running a platform mbean server. However, trying to create a one off would put the code in the same boat because java 6 could introduce new vm args that no one thought to test the combinations out with the tomcat server adapter. However, were startup and shutdown vm arg fields available, I would have just added the correct args to startup and made sure they weren't in shutdown.

I agree with your approach, but this level of change would need to go in WTP 2.0. If this is to be addressed in WTP 1.5.x, then something less ambitious will be needed, which is the context for my specific suggestions. In your case, how important is it to do something about this in WTP 1.5.x?

(In reply to comment #10) > I agree with your approach, but this level of change would need to go in WTP > 2.0. If this is to be addressed in WTP 1.5.x, then something less ambitious > will be needed, which is the context for my specific suggestions. In your > case, how important is it to do something about this in WTP 1.5.x? >
It's very important as we can't use WTP for stopping/restart the connector. We either kill the process or have to keep the shutdown.[sh|bat] script on the desktop to properly stop the tomcat instance. Can you comment on how this is a 2.0 "level of change"? The way I see it, the 2 textfields can be added with 100% backward compatibility. The first text field, "Startup VM arguments" is already there labeled "VM arguments". That textfield needs to be renamed. In keeping with backward compatibility, any previously defined VM arguments" will get auto-magically moved to the new "Startup VM arguments" textfield. Another textfield needs to be slid in below "Startup VM arguments" labeled "Shutdown VM arguments". This field will be empty since it didn't exist before. Finally the code would have been updated to call getStartupVMArguments() and getShutdownVMArguments() at the appropriate times. Were I not patching maven and pde build to work together nowadays, I would have already done this and submitted a patch. I agree I have,t looked at the code but the mental thought process works out to be a very small addition, not a deletion or big modification.

What gets implemented for WTP 2.0 should be the done the "right" way. To me, this means potentially making these fields available for all servers, not just Tomcat. Also there are details to be worked out. For example, if the "Enable security" is checked in the Tomcat configuration and a user has added their own separate "java.security.policy" system property to the startup arguments, what happens? Does one silently win, a warning dialog pops up, or something else. Is there validation that displays an error before such a conflict is created? Also, should there be separate arguments for debug, run, and profile. If there is a need for this, it would be nice if you didn't lose the ability to switch directly from run to debug because you have to manually modify the arguments. The scale of all this I think is too big for the 1.5.x stream.
Doing something simpler but similar in WTP 1.5.1, but just for Tomcat, will still be a fair amount of work and complicate doing things "right" in WTP 2.0. Unfortunately, though my WTP work is focused strictly on Tomcat support, I'm a part time WTP committer and my day job in the past hasn't left many cycles to devote to WTP. This is the main reason not a lot changed in the Tomcat support between 1.0 and 1.5. I'm finding more cycles these days, but it's not unlimited. I have to decide what is the best use of those cycles. Tim, as a component lead, has a much wider focus in WTP and I believe would face the same kind of decission for that reason. Thus, if this issue is to be addressed in WTP 1.5.x, I think it will need to be a limited, low risk, minimum cycle, type fix, such as what was suggested earlier.
Fair enough. I too have the "anchor" of of a day job getting in the way of my open source contributions. :)

Agreed with Larry. We can't make any text/UI changes in the 1.5.x stream, so unless this is blocking (well, you can still kill the process...) we should focus effort on implementing the right fix for 2.0.

bug.short_desc: manifest.mf validator misses a missing end quote

long_desc.thetext:
In one of our WTP bundles, I've just noticed it had a missing end quote, at the very end of the Require-Bundle header:
Require-Bundle: org.eclipse.core.resources;bundle-version="[3.2.0,4.0)", org.eclipse.core.runtime;bundle-version="[3.2.0,4.0)", org.eclipse.jdt.core;bundle-version="[3.2.0,4.0)", org.eclipse.wst.common.project.facet.core;bundle-version="[1.1.100,1.2.0) Eclipse-LazyStart: true

I've marked as minor since "if it runs, it runs" :) .... but ... since that might not always be true in future (if someone changes the underlying parsers), then errors could start happening in "old, previously running" code. So, I thought it deserved writing up.
Not sure how literal this part of the spec is, but in OSGI 4 spec, section 3.2.5, it says <quote> Note that the use of a comma in the version range requires it to be enclosed in double quotes. For example: Import-Package: com.acme.foo;version="[1.23, 2)", com.acme.bar;version="[4.0, 5.0)" </quote>

This is coming from ManifestElement.parseHeader(). A BundleException is not thrown if the header value is missing an ending quote for the last element.
Tom, any chance we can look at ManifestElement so it can validate the last quote in a Manifest header? If a BundleException is thrown, PDE will flag the header as having an invalid format.

bug.short_desc: Publish fails after "Move to Workspace" - tmp0 deleted but publish0.xml not

long_desc.thetext:
Version: Callisto production release.
Test scenario: - In servers view, create a (in my case Tomcat 5.5) server with one or more modules. - Right click, publish. - Verify in .metadata/.plugins/org.eclipse.wst.server.core that you have: - publish.xml relating the server key to publish0.xml - tmp-data.xml relating the server key to tmp0 directory - tmp0 directory has modules deployed under webapps/{modulename} - Right click server in Servers view and select Move to Workspace (something those of us using Team (CVS or SVN) with Server configs tend to do. - Right click, publish - Look in tmp0/webapps - No modules have been published, only the ROOT directory
Why?
It seems to be the case that there is an operation that deletes a server that does not remove the publish.xml entries, therefore, when the same server key re-appears, the publish engine thinks that most of the server content is up to date.
Other test scenarios that are similar: - Create server with module - Delete the server - Notice that publish.xml entries still exist, yet no tmp0 does.
and: - Move to workspace (at this point publishing failing) - Shut down Eclipse - Clean out org.eclipse.wst.server.core dir. - Start Eclipse - Publish should be succeeding - Delete the server - Restore the server files (either via Team->Revert.. operation or Restore from Local History) - Publish -> No modules are published.
The solution seems to be that when a server is deleted, all references that contain that server's key must also be deleted.
